description.text:
This is an SPI based Stepper controller with a load of cool features.
What this means is that the CPU sends a command like, go to position X, and the stepper does this without the CPU needing to worry about keeping position registers or time slicing to make the motor turn, etc. The Steppers controllers also have cool features like hardware acceleration/deceleration, stall detection and various other Stepper related controls including 1/128 microstepping making it so smooth. The only down side to the chip is that it's quite expensive, at $13 a pop (NZD so around $10US). Anyway, this board will fit my Mighty Mega Mother board and should not be used in the standard Mighty board as it's not compatible (Sorry).
The chips datasheet is available at http://www.st.com/internet/analog/product/248592.jsp?WT.ac=motor_control_L6470_250610 Fits in the Mighty Mega board http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:19386

comments.text: it's a pity this chip is mostly useless for 3d printing since it has absolutely no way to synchronise multiple axes which we require for geometric accuracy.
comments.author: triffid_hunter

comments.text: If you connect them together in a SPI daisy chain you can do synced moves. What is hard with the part is not coming to a full stop after each move. You can't pipeline moves so you have to be able to send the next move at the end of the previous within one microstep time or there will be a pause. I gave up one using this part in a printer because of this. Not having a dir pin means you can't really use it as a simple multi axis stepper driver because of the sync problem.

description.text:
I loved the 2x e3d upgrade but was worried the fan ducts were going to break with all the shaking and didn't think they snapped on very tightly. Went ahead and upgraded and redesigned.

And then i just kept going, this is a full redesign of cadsys' e3d upgrade for the 2x:

hardware:
2 x M3x18 or longer - carriage to hotend assembly
3 x M3x12 or longer - top cap to hotend assembly
2 x M3 washer - optional for the top cap
1 x good ol popscicle stick - X axis endstop
5 x M3 nuts
k type thermocouple for e3d:https://www.matterhackers.com/store/printer-accessories/e3d-type-k-thermocouple-cartridge

software:
Just need to reverse the direction on the two extruders when using cadsys's upside down rear mount extruder mounts.

directions:
assemble E3D extruders, use the kType thermocouples instead of what came with them.
push the 5 3mm nuts into their holes and line them up with the bolt holes, should be snug and they shouldn't fall out easily.
Cut off about 1.375" of a popsicle stick and glue into the matching cutout on the hot end mount.
Secure the clamp to the top of the hot ends with the 12mm bolts. Cinch down each of the bolts before tightening anything! Check to make sure the clamp is level and then start tightening each of the 3 screws about a quarter to half turn at a time, don't over tighten the clamp to the point you are bending it too much.
Screw the fans onto the fan ducts, make absolutely positive they are blowing DOWN. Ideally the wires are pointing in or forward.
Snap the fan ducts onto the hot end, they should feel very secure. with no play but they will still rotate easily.
Use the two 18mm screw to attach the assembly into your X carriage.

Wire it all up and you're good to go!

connect thermocouples as shown in the picture, if yours come with different colored terminals or wires use a DMM with the ability to read a thermocouple to make sure you don't get the wires backwards, this can cause a pretty large error in temp reading at extrusion temps.

getting the two nozzles level is pretty difficult but spending time getting the hot ends to the exact same height helps then from there shim the side of the hot end holder with paper as shown in the last picture, it took a single piece for me to get them level enough that they dont interfere with each other but still stick to the build plate well.

Slicer Settings:
Simplify gave much better results even with the same settings, but the stock maker bot desktop still works! Just turn up the retract distance a little thanks to the bowden.

these are some sample settings that worked for ABS and nylon through this printer, it is fairly robust and works with most settings unless you're going for the perfect print in which case tweak away!
3-4.75mm retract
2500-5000mm/min retract speed
4800-5100mm/min print speed (helps a lot)

description.text: Over the summer I read and completed Hellboy (comic books). In the King Arthur arch, I really loved the villain Nimue (the goddess of blood & queen of witches). Immediately I knew that I could design and 3D print a pretty accurate version of her helmet.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator Z18

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Print in Two Pieces

The bottom piece prints upside down. Each piece prints snuggly on a MakerBot Replicator Z18.

Foam Additions

I made foam shapes that fit into the helmet. The foam is interested into the crow's wings and the cheek guards. I wanted foam for the cheek guards because I wanted to be able to turn my head. The crow's wings could be potential sharp if I accidentally hit someone with them, so I opted for foam there too. There is no recipe to make the wings. I used a reference picture and measured.

Neoprene Foam 1/2"

Glue

I used Hot Glue although I wouldn't recommend this method as it destroys the designed tolerance between the two halves. I would recommend a thinner glue like super glue. A good glue would be Zap A Gap with the accelerator. Make sure you wear gloves and follow instructions.

Zap-A-Gap
Zip Kicker

Stone Spray Texture

I didn't sand the pieces much. Instead I used a canned texture called Stone Spray. This is a spray paint that textures your print like it's stone. It's a little strange to use, and takes awhile to dry.

Ruse-Oleum Stone Spray

Black Layer

Once the stone spray is dry, apply two to three coats of matte black spray paint.

Matte Black Spray Paint

Silver Dry Brush

Once the matte black is dry, take a large bristle brush and dab with silver paint. Pat the access paint off with a paper towel and apply the brush in a dabbing motion to the helmet.

Metallic Silver Craft Paint
House Paint Brush

description.text:
The MicroCube is a small, inexpensive 3D printer, designed around the cheap 28BYJ-48 stepper motors (files for Nema17 included except Z axis). The structure of the printer is based on an exoskeleton, which also serves as the smooth rods for the y-axis. The printer type is an H-bot style printer using a fishing line. In order to provide enough torque for the extruder, two steppers are used in series (or single Nema17 version). Due to the limitations of the 28BYJ-48 steppers, the precision is limited as well as the print speed (2-3 times slower than a standard printer).

Video of print: https://youtu.be/JlPdN9ktdqY

Features:

  • Low cost ~100€
  • Easy to build
  • Printable Area of 120mm x 115mm x 95mm
  • Small footprint 220mm x 220mm
  • Low noise during print (with 28BYJ-48 steppers ~50dB, with Nema17 ~60dB)
  • Upgradeable with Nema17 motors for higher speed and precision

Electronics

For the use of the 28BYJ-48, the bipolar hack is required. A description how this can be done is available at http://www.electronicsmayhem.com/?p=13 , all 5 motors must be prepared as described. The wires of the motors are quite short and need to be extended, at this point, the connector could also be set in the correct sequence to match the RAMPs connector:

2B = yellow * (pin1)
2A = blue
1A = pink
1B = orange

At the RAMPs board, the current limit needs to be set before powering it the first time, following values could be used as Vref, fine tuning will be required due to production tolerances of the motors. During testing, X/Y/Z steppers didn’t lose any step, but they heated up slightly.

X/Y/Z driver = 75mV
E driver = 150mV

Mechanics

The printer is designed as an H bot, due to the small size, a fishing line is used along with ball bearings which are usually used in the extruder to guide the fishing line.
The extruder with two motors instead of one is used in order to provide enough torque for a direct drive bowden setup, the tension of the spring must be balanced not to harm the motors or gears but also to provide enough force for extrusion.

Software

Firmware used for the MicroCube is Marlin 1.1.0 RC7, the configuration.h is provided along the files as a starting point to get the printer setup quickly. Here are some informations about the set values for the MicroCube:

Since Arduino Mega with RAMPs is used, Motherboard must be set to:

ifndef MOTHERBOARD

I based this design off of user Tech2C's design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1632847) as it was the best I've seen. Hope he doesn't mind.

It is designed to work with the hexagon cooler, but will probably also work with the E3D V6.

Screw holes are M5 and meant to be screwed into.

Printer:

Cobblebot Vanguard Prusa i3 Hybrid

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

<= 0.2

Infill:

at least 30% for mount, 100% for Duct

Notes:

No support on the duct, as there are tiny supports included in the model which can be broken off with a knife. Support required for the mount part as there is a bridge which needs to be square.

V1.1

  1. Surround duct size increased to make more room for the hotend to prevent melting when running hot temps.
  2. Air outlet gap width increased for more airflow and reduced pressure, because air was being pushed out of gaps between the fan and duct rather than fully out of the surround outlet.
  3. Duct shortened as it was too long.
  4. Added screw head clearance for Mount mounting screws.
  5. Increased length of clamp screw hole to accommodate longer screws.

V1.0

Surround cooler released for testing. All is present to use except the lock part that clamps the hotend in place. This part can be used from the aforementioned part on which i based my design. (Show Tech2C some love while you're there)

description.text:
This is my bike light that uses a GU5.3/MR16 12v LED spotlight and a cheap Li-po.

I wanted a decent amount of light for cycling on dark cycle paths and figured I could use a 12v LED spot and some spare Li-po packs.

You will need:

1 x GU5.3/MR16 12v LED Spot (available for not much money from DIY stores - I found a 4.8w 350 lumen one from Sainsburys for just over a quid)
1 x GU5.3/MR16 wire socket (ebay/maplin etc)
1 x Battery - I leave that choice up to you, but I am using a spare Turnigy 7.4v 2 cell 1Ah Li-po. Initial tests are encouraging with this pack lasting over 2hrs.
Some wire, sockets, heat shrink etc - Again the choice is up to you. Use what you have handy. Wireup the led to suit.
Some M4 nuts and bolts.

Print:

1 x Light Body
1 x Light Rim (Optional)
1 x Mount Arm (Note: I've not tested the arm as the light body fits in place of the front reflector and uses that arm)

The LED was a really tight fit and I had to scrape some plastic off the edge of the led and the housing. I've added some extra clearance to the model but needs testing.

I glued the led in place with super glue followed by the light rim and more super glue around the edge. Time will tell if it can stand the knocks and bumps.

Fit the light to the mounting arm and fit to bike!

title: Bottle cage mount holder - Metabikes recumbent

description.text:
This is a bottle cage mount holder for both chainstays, on a Metabikes Metaphrastic recumbent.  
My recumbent is a rear disc brake type, so I don't need the threaded holes on each chainstay to mount a caliper brake.  
However, one of the threaded hole (the left one) is used to clip the rear hydraulic hose.  
Each mount holder is mounted with a bolt (on the upper side) and with a zip tie (on the lower side). The zip tie is inserted in a little tunnel created inside the holder body (See the plane cut for details)  
To hold the bottle cage on the lower side, a 8mm nut is needed, and a short bolt (about 10mm long, bolt head not included).  
Finally, I fastened the rear hydraulic hose with 2 zip ties on the left mount holder.

I work on a GNU/Linux workstation (Ubuntu 13.10)
I used at first openscad to setup the model and export it to STL format. Then I used netfabb-basic to automatically repair my 3D model. The STL file I uploaded is the repaired one. Feel free to re-use the openscad source but don't forget to correct the STL export !

description.text:
I had an idea to take advantage of one of 3D printing's greatest hurdles, air-printing, to create a realistic looking Christmas pine tree. By creating arrays of thin perimeters for the branches, I was able to get something that looks almost like blown-glass. It took me three iterations of branch shape, radial spacing, and vertical spacing to finally get a result I'm happy with. Please note my suggested print settings to ensure a successful print.

I recommend printing in something a bit hot and oozy like PETg or TPU for the best results.

Note that if you print a plate of them, like I did, you may end up with odd branches where perimeters start on the end of branches instead of at the core. I had to do a little bit of clean-up before taking the photo of the 'forest.'

Edit 12/5/2016: Not sure why thingiview is not showing up for the stl. S3D didn't yell about any manifold problems, but I'll try running a repair and re-upload. Added a quick rendering in the meantime.

This is a major modification to Nightlight1. The inner light shape is the same, but I replaced the outer shape with a hexagonal grid that I developed for things like colandars or open baskets. This is the most complex design I have made yet, so here is more than you could ever want to know about it.

  1. Photo 1 shows the light off during the day with the LED puck light that goes inside. This type of LED light is quite common; they come in both battery and wall power versions. Search for "LED puck" and you will find lots of alternatives.
  2. Photo 2 is the light on during the day; photo 3 is the same but at night.
  3. Photo 4 is a top view; the inner surface is round, but the outer cage is oval. I thought this made the whole thing more interesting.
  4. Photo 5 is a close-up of the hex grid. Note that there are both hexagon and diamond shapes. This is the result of the hexagons being grouped parallel to each other rather than offset like they are in chicken wire fences. Cagelight1 will have offset hexagons.
  5. Photo 6 shows the waffle shape I put on the bottom. This reduces the amount of filament required, makes for easier removal from the print bed, and prevents warping due to cooling contraction.

The part printed in 33 1/4 hours using a 0.200 mm layer height. The STL file is named BK1 for BigKahuna1; it is the first part made by combining the geometry definitions for 4 different parts: the circular light shape, the light bottom/LED holder, the hex cage, and the hex cage waffle bottom.

description.text:
Everyone who dabbles in electronics is familiar with the annoyance of storage boxes with compartments that don't seal up to the bottom of the box, right? Small parts like resistors just roll under the "walls" and get all mixed up. I wanted something to organize resistors in enclosed compartments. There are some cool sewing organizers, systems of complete boxes within a larger box, but those solutions are no fun -- they don't involve 3D printing.

The actual containers here are clear plastic test tubes I bought from Amazon, link below. I've uploaded models for two versions of the tube holder, a single holder and a fiver. Both styles have connecting holes; just print the "connector" model and put them together.

The connecting holes are d=10mm and to be flush on the back the knobs on the connector straps are h=2. The knobs are d1=9.25 and d2=9. While they do pressure fit, I didn't dial them in to truly "lock." My intent was to have them just provide stability for each other while lying in a shallow tool box. I'd suggest gluing them together permanently if you're going to carry a box around or mount this vertically on a workbench wall, pegboard, etc.

The OpenSCAD file is also uploaded in case you'd like to make connectors that span more than two holders, create 3-packs or 10-packs, whatever you like.

Next step is to find or print a box that a bunch of these will fit nicely in.

description.text:
I was never really happy with the x axis on this printer and was getting a lot of ringing because of the lack of stiffness of the x axis. I got the idea from Sonny Lowe to use the open builds v wheel system for my x axis. I really wanted to use the E3D titan extruder but with the extruder directly on the front of the axis it really took away from my z height. To get around this I decided to move the carriage to the top of the axis instead of directly in front. Doing it this way got me from ~150mm z height to now ~180mm z height. It also puts the weight of the extruder more directly over the v rail which imo is a better idea.

I have been using a tiny 13oz/in stepper for the extruder which so far has worked excellent because of the gear ratio of the Titan extruder.

I have attached plenty of pictures so hopefully it will not be too difficult to figure out how to put together. I decided to use printed couplers for the acme rods which have been working great so far. Also i have used thread inserts for the z nuts which i got from mcmaster carr. They are heat set inserts for plastic so just heat them up with a soldering iron and press them in.

The diameter of the spool holder is 51mm and was designed for Esun petg rolls. I can also upload different sizes depending on what the needs are. Any questions just ask!

title: X Carriage Alignment Tool for Geeetech Prusa i3
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Update 1/15/18 I added a version that might work better in tight spaces. It should be the same height as the shorter one, but it's always best to print a pair; one of the file here, and the other a mirror of that file.

This Thing includes two nearly identical tools and one that should fit tight spaces better. You use a pair of one of them to set the X carriage perpendicular to the threaded rods, and parallel to the horizontal plane of the printer. One tool grips the smooth rod tighter and may be taller. Since I only used the original, I can't comment on the other two.

I made these tools for a family member, but never used them at the time. I forgot about them until I recently had a reason to readjust my X carriage settings.

There are several steps here. If your printer is/was operating normally, start at step A. If you have removed or are replacing the X carriage, start at D and then restart at A.

A. WHEN THE ALIGNMENT GETS DISTURBED DUE TO A CRASH INTO THE BED OR A STEPPER MOTOR THAT DROPS STEPS.
If the carriage is noticeably no longer parallel to the bed, it is probably best to manually adjust one side to get the carriage reasonably close to parallel to the frame of the printer. With the printer power removed, turn the stepper motor coupler(s) Clockwise (as viewing the front of the stepper) to RAISE the Carriage. Turn Counterclockwise to lower the carriage.

Once it is acceptable, raise the carriage using the computer or firmware adjustment routines to place the alignment tools on the smooth rods. Then lower the carriage so it rests or is close to resting on the tools.

B. FINAL ALIGNMENT OF CARRIAGE
The final step is to adjust each stepper motor shaft to position the X carriage a few thousandths above the stepper motor coupler (the thickness of a piece of printer paper), ensuring that the coupler-spring is not compressed. Probably a good way to do this is to put a piece of paper between the top of the alignment tool and the linear bearing holder. Adjust the stepper motor position manually to lower it down on to paper and stop when the paper is touching the paper, but with minimal pressure. Both sides should get the same treatment, whatever scheme you use. You can raise the carriage using the motors and remove the tools now, or after the next step.

C. PLACING SYNC MARKS ON EACH STEPPER MOTOR COUPLER.
The carriage should now be parallel to the printer frame. The next step will add visual marking to the stepper couplers so that is easy to see if the stepper positions ever get out of sync (and upset the bed leveling).

This amounts to nothing more than a mark in the same position on each stepper motor coupler, see photo. Since the carriage is aligned, you can set it in any position for marking both couplers. Remove the tools if they are still present. FWIW, rather than marking, I like to loosen one coupler and position it so it matches the second one.

As you use the printer, the marks should always remain in the same angular position. There is nothing in the printer design that allows the printer to know if they get out of sync. A bad adjustment on a stepper motor driver potentiometer can cause a stepper to occasionally drop steps. YouTube contains videos on the adjustment procedure. All it takes is a voltmeter, a small screw driver, and maybe three hands.
END OF ADJUSTMENT

D. PROCEDURE FOR CARRIAGE INSTALLATION DURING INITIAL ASSEMBLY OR REASSEMBLY.
I haven't done this, and I'm writing this procedure from memory and recalling how clumsy it was as recommended in the build manual. If some steps don't work, please suggest some changes. I'm not likely to build another.

As you are getting ready to install the X carriage assembly, rather than install the threaded rods into the X carriage, set them aside and insert them later. Assemble the X carriage including the smooth rods. Attach the tools to each smooth rod near the bottom.

With the top plates removed, place the X carriage into position and lower the smooth rods into the hole in the frame, with each side of the X carriage resting on an alignment tool.

Loosely attach the top plates, placing the smooth rod through the hole for the smooth rod. With the top plates installed, the carriage will be stable, resting on the tool, which rests on the frame base.

I'm assuming the stepper motors and couplers are attached prior to the above steps, so now, the bottom coupler should be tightened onto the stepper motor shaft, and the upper coupling should be completely loosened to receive the threaded rod.

One at a time, remove the top plates and thread the rod down through the brass nut until it just enters the coupling but does not bottom out. Replace each top plate. Again, it does not have to be tightened, but the threaded rod should be able to be turned by hand with the top plate in place. If it binds, add a drop of oil.

At this point, the X carriage should be in-place, resting on the tools, with the threaded rod resting slightly above the bottom of the coupling cavity.

The next step is to thread the rods, one at a time, down until they just touch the bottom of the cavity, and before they start to lift the carriage more than a few thousandths off the tools. At this point the top coupling can be tightened, tightly!

There is more to do; the final steps will be accomplished, by restarting at step A.
= = = = = = = = = =
INFORMATION YOU CAN LIVE WITHOUT:
When I built my printer, I eventually came to the point where you had to level the bed. At the time I thought that the word level really had nothing to do with what we were doing, but I knew what they meant, and I didn't know a better name for it. What that adjustment does is adjust the printer bed so it is parallel to the X carriage travel (however good or bad that may be). It turns out there is a better word for the procedure and it is TRAMMEL. As a noun, it can be used to refer to a tool for trammeling. As a verb, it refers to making a mechanical alignment or adjustment, which is exactly what carriage/bed leveling is all about. Thanks to GZUMWALT, Thingiverse designer extraordinaire, for introducing me to a new word.

title: Pirate crossed cutlass curtain rod holder

description.text:
My son wanted a pirate theme for his bedroom. We got a few accessories and a very cool shower curtain. But pirate-themed curtain rod holders are hard to find, so I came up with this.  
These fit 3/4 inch PVC (which should normally only have printing on one side, so it can be hidden). I would recommend the heavier PVC rated for 400psi since the lighter PVC (pictured) tends to sag a bit in the middle on a 6-foot span.  
These brackets are end-socketed which means you need to get your rings on the rod before mounting the second bracket. See instructions for a suggested mounting strategy.

• Decide whether you are going to support the rod only on the ends or if you need middle supports.

  • You should be able to print with a 0.3mm layer height. If your printer supports M600 (change filament) and you want to have the crossed cutlasses in a different color (as I did with silver) you want to put the M600 line in your gcode output just after G1 Z54.650 (you get better results if one layer is printed in the base color before changing).

  • Get a length of 400psi 3/4 inch PVC (commonly available for around $2-3 at any building supply place). You'll also need drywall anchors or appropriate screw hardware.

  • Mount one of your end brackets (NOT both just yet). You should be able to use the holes as drilling guides. If you have middle supports you can mount them at this time (note that middle supports only work if you have multiple curtain panels).

  • Insert one end of your PVC pipe through any middle supports (if you're using them) and the end support you've attached to the wall already.

  • Position the other end bracket where you want it horizontally (keeping the PVC pipe level) and mark the PVC pipe halfway through the bracket.

  • Take the PVC pipe down and cut it at the mark.

  • Put the other end bracket (the one you haven't mounted yet) on the PVC pipe, make sure everything is level and drill your holes in the wall for mounting. Do not insert screws yet, but you can put the anchors in after taking down the end bracket and PVC pipe.

  • Make sure you have the mounting screws and screwdriver within reach, and put one end of the PVC pipe in the bracket which was mounted in step 1, then put your curtain rings over the pipe (I used the C-shaped shower rings printed in the same color as the end brackets - see picture). Now you can secure the end bracket using screws.

Lets face it, those christmas tree stands that have the legs, the bucket and the three screws aren't the easiest of things to use. It's fine if your tree stump fits snugly into the bucket, but if your stump is too narrow then the bottom of the stump can slip around on the bottom of the bucket, especially once you've added water, and you have to make those three screw insanely tight to stop the tree moving around.

Use one of these - put it in the bottom of the bucket, spikes upwards, and the stump of the tree rests on it. The stump can't then slide around, and the screws can do a better job of holding the tree upright.

For the other case, when the stump is too wide for the bucket, and you have to hack away at it with whatever meager tools you have at your disposal.. I can't help you there i'm afraid.

For printing, scale the x and y axes to give you a diameter just smaller than your bucket, and scale the z axis for the height of spikes you want (affects printing time). Resolution isn't important, so whatever prints quickest for you. No support needed, though a raft might make it easier to remove from the printing bed (you don't even need to remove the raft afterward). The piece is load-bearing so should ideally be as solid as possible, so infill is a compromise between how solid you want it and how long you're prepared to let it take to print.

title: E3D Titan Extruder Upgrade for Prusa Steel Igus bearings

description.text:
I'm building a Prusa Steel v4 3d printer with a 20x30 cm printbed. I will use a Titan extruder from E3D, a short body Nema17 motor and Igus bearings. The Igus bearings are very sensitive to compression so they will stick very easily. I used the excellent E3D Titan Extruder Upgrade for Prusa i3 from GyroBot as a base and changed to geometry of the bearing holders to be able to use Igus bearings. I used a 2.3 mm drill and an M3 taps to make the threads. I use a short body Nema17 motor and the weight of this package is less than the weight of a normal Nema17 motor. The reason I want to use this type of extruder instead of a bowden type is that I plan to print very soft Filaflex.

Update 2016-12-12
I use the x-axis parts designed by toolson http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1036871. The first version was based on the design from Gyrobot. To make it compatible with toolsons design I had to offset the belts 5mm. I named the new part x_carriage_toolson.stl. The yellow part is compatible with the part from Gyrobot. The red part is compatible with parts from toolson.

Update 2016-12-19. Added a holder for the BLTouch. I don't know if it will work so please let me know if you find any problems with the remix. It was a bit difficult because the Igus bearings needs to be pushed in from the sides and the holder from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1552022 would interfere with that, This part is made as two separate objects so that it can be easily reconfigured. It needs to be printed with support. You also need the rest of the parts from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1552022 to make a complete unit.

Update 2017-01-01 Added a new version for bltouch holder and imuu8 bearings.

Update 2017-06-21 I use the fan holder from here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1571526

Vertex K8400

Only the version with the BLTouch needs to be printed with support.

How to make the Igus bearings fit

If you just print this part and try to use it, the bearings will probaby stick. The trick to make it work is to print it in PLA. First mount the bearings and the steel rods. Then heat the holder using a heatgun so that it gets a little warm. Don't melt it, just heat it enough for the plasic to become a little soft. It will harden again when it cools down and the bearings will fit without being under preassure. To make the bearings stay in place and not slide out of the holder they need to be held in place by M3 screws and a washer as you can see in the pictures.

description.text:
In the photo of it, the battery is not snapped down in its slot yet. I have not cut the power wire yet and it's my smoke detector battery. So it's going back where it came from. Battery snaps in extra tight an don't want to have to fight it back out. Ipad had trouble with the unit on so picture is with it off. Works great. Really like that little bugger :)

Bought this electronic tester on ebay for 14 bucks and it is truly amazing. Wish they had such item and price when i was learning electronics. It checks about all but integrated components. Works great as far as i've seen. Don't have on hand other testers to cross check, but normally what you need is just a good bad test and this thing does that and a lot more. Will find transistor pin out check for npn or pnp beta and frequency check ect. All components connect any way you want to connect them, thats the best part.

Made this top and bottom to fit which includes a few nice features. The top is a near snap on to the bottom with out much need for screws. There are holes for screws if printer prints them well, otherwise it makes a boss area for drilling and setting screws. There is a slot for the battery wire to pull out so you can cut one or other to install a switch. I just cut the red wire so i can just twist tie it when in use. The battery will drain in storage so a disconnect or battery removal is needed. Made kinda silly but neat to me holders on both sides with holes to slide the mini wire clips in to keep from loosing them. Some things just can't be found when needed with me and i think those wire clips would be in that type shape.The battery connector can be screwed in or just glue it in.

Be extra careful with the screen ribbon that raps around the board and connects the display. It will be fragile and may break and disable the whole tester. Take care and no problems will happen.

There is one problem though, all works great but i forgot to include a tiny recess for the bump on the back of the board where the two power wires loop around the board. You will just have to maybe drill, chip-out or use some form of tool to chip out so the board fits nice and flat. Thats what i did and works great. Don't try to bend. The screen will break or a solder joint come loose. Pocket knife will do, just dont loose a finger in the process.. :)

Hope you enjoy, have fun and happy printing.

Rick.

Search ebay for mega328 to get you one, real nice.
"Mega328 Transistor Tester Diode Triode Capacitance ESR Meter MOS/PNP/NPN L/C/R"

Update: I forgot to mention that i plan to cut a small piece of plastic acrylic to drop in the screen display slot to protect it from bumps and knocks. 2-5/16 X 1-9/16 inches i think will fit prefect. May have to file a small amount but will make much more durable. After all that's why i made the enclosure to start with to protect the board.

title: Runcam Owl adapter and minimosd mount for Spaceonefpv aero pod

description.text:
This is a little adapter I drew up based on my previous runcam owl adapter. I'm transferring that build over to the SpaceoneFPV 220X frame with Aero pod designed by @babar121 and my original design doesnt seem to fit. I fugured it would make a clean mounting spot for the OSD as well. It was designed for the standard camera mounting version of the pod, not the short camera one.

I printed the one in the pictures in TPU but ABS or other stiffer plastic ought to be alright as well. It accepts two m3 3.8mm depth heat-set thermoplactic threaded inserts. These help it to screw in securely, and wont wear out over repeated installation and removal of the camera. Theyre available here at McMaster-Carr as part number 94180A331, although only in bags of 100 minimum... They do come in handy frequently if you do much printing however. You will also need some small m3 button head screws, around 4mm seems perfect.

They install with a soldering iron. mcmaster sells a special one and special tool for installing, but for home use a standard iron and a pair of pliers is enough. rest iron firmly onto the insert but apply most of the force required to push it in using the pliers. broken a soldering iron heater element before trying to use only the iron to put it in. YMMV.

The micro minimosd fits neatly on the back, and the connector for the owl camera should fit cleanly through the hole as well. It seems to test fit well in my copy of the babar121's pod, but I havent flow it yet. I plan to use a little transfer tape to hold the camera into the mount, and either more tape or some hot glue to hold the minimosd into its mounting location.

I've provided the .sldprt file, feel free to modify however you like, post remixes, etc.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: A cable chain for those of us who are a bit paranoid about the bed cable bundle being caught under the bed. Or who just want it to look nicer.

I guess this is more a solution waiting for a problem type of project but you have to admit it looks nice. I needed 12 segments plus the end pieces to complete my chain. I don't know about the variance of cable length so YMMV of course.  
Assemble the complete chain before mounting it in the machine. The tolerances aren't super tight but I made the pieces quite rigid to keep them from flexing too much. Once the chain is mounted it starts getting tricky adding pieces due to lack of space.  
The angled piece replaces the original little black clip that secures the cable to the bed, just unscrew it and replace with this thing.  
To secure the bottom end piece I used double sided tape since I didn't want to drill any holes in the machine. Make sure you angle it correctly so that the chain doesn't curve under the bed. I suggest that you manually move the bed up and down a few times to make sure everything clears before letting the machine do its thing on its own (don't ask me how I know, let's just say this wasn't the first design...).

A Mini "Monster" Truck - I decided to make the name a little more literal, and I'm hoping to make a few more of these.

I'm dangerously low on white filament so I had to print this at a reduced size, unfortunately. As soon as I order more I'm going to reprint this, as honestly I kind of think it's fun.
I'll likely create custom supports for it at that time, so it can be printed a little easier.

Entry for the Thingiverse #RemixChallenge

One of my earliest 3D Models I'd made was a simple skull - I wanted to learn to create models from pictures instead of just free-handing it and figured a skull would be a challenging place to start.

When this challenge appeared, I knew I wanted to take something from my old projects and give them a new life - when I saw the Mini Monster Truck, I decided a "Monster" Truck series would be a lot of fun, and remembered the ole cranium collecting dust in my Blender/Old Saves/ folder.

However, my original model was rather dated - a mere 2,200 triangles (Picture Below). My first step was to update the skull itself, smooth it out, and bring it up to snuff so that the printed model wouldn't be obviously polygonal.

After smoothing it out, I had to reshape the innards - I had modeled the original skull to be hollow, but still manifold. I had to tear out the inner walls and create volume in most of the skull - but I wanted the Nose hole to be an actual hole, so I had to model around a nasal passage.
I'm glad I went this route, as I think filling the nose in as I did with the eyes wouldn't look as good.

Next, I simply had to detach the Monster Truck from the base piece (Created by Jakejake) with the suspension, and pop the skull on top - which took far longer than I'd like to admit.

I then did a few model tests to ensure the wheels would clear the jaw, and make sure everything would still fit properly in the end.

Final step was simply to print, assemble, and take pictures. I'm pretty happy with how it turned out and intend to print a few more, and create some more "Monster" trucks in the future.

Original Skull Model, ~2,200 triangles. Updated Skull Model, ~14,000 Triangles. It's alive! ALIVE!

If you have the most recent Printrbot LCD kit (with the wooden enclosure) and a Printrbot Simple with a tower (standard or tall) this will allow you to mount your LCD on the outside of the tower; it retains the two wooden faceplates, but replaces the triangular sides and the center bit (with the PB logo) with printed parts, so you can clip the LCD to the handle opening on the tower. The handle can still be used, and you never need to worry about dropping your LCD, or knocking it off the desk.

UPDATE: I re-uploaded "LCD_Clip_V2.stl". I fixed the part orientation so it will print correctly.   
Print two copies of "LCD Sides.stl" and one copy of "LCD Clip V2.stl"  
These parts should fit on a standard simple bed. I know they fit on my simple with build volume upgrade; the parts pictured were printed on a Replicator 2.  
I printed with two shells (perimiters) and 15% infill. no support needed.   
insert the tabs on either end of the clip part into a side part. Make sure the main clip is facing down and to the back (flat edge of the clip to the front, with the cutout on the back-left, to allow clearance for the ribbon cable) the side pieces have tabs that should face forward.  
the three pieces are a snug fit together, but shouldn't need filing or trimming. a little persuasion with a small hammer (just a tap or two) should get them snugged up. you shouldn't need glue.  
insert the tabs on the sides into the recessed areas on the back of the LCD faceplate. the clip goes towards the top of the LCD. Use the two screws and nuts from the original assembly to secure the new assembly to the faceplate. If you assembled the original LCD, it should be a no-brainer.  
If assembly (or my discription of assembly) is confusing, refer to the "LCD Clip assembly.stl" file to see how the pieces should fit together  
Pass the cable up, and through the handle hole in the tower, from the outside. Insert the clip through the same hole, from the outside and push down to clip onto the tower case. If the fit is not snug enough, fold a small piece of paper in half, fold it over the spot on the case where the clip goes, and press the clip over it. I did this, and now it's snug, doesn't slip at all, and can still be unclipped. If the piece of paper is small enough, you won't see it, and it will still be a clean install.  
Route your ribbon down to your printrboard, you may need to get creative to keep the cable from rubbing on carriages, rods, etc. Mine was easy, but it's a tall tower. Don't be afraid to use tape, double sided tape, zip ties, etc. to get it routed and clear of any moving parts. FYI, I was able to route the cable with none of the above, but I may still add some double-sided tape to stick down the ribbon eventually.   
Enjoy your new LCD mount!  
Let me know if you made this and what you think!

description.text:
Just another direct extruder design. For direct driving with NEMA 17 motor, standard Prusa i3 X carriage and a JHead type hotend. 40mm fan support for the hotend body.  
I decide to design this extruder due to the problems I had trying to print 1.75mm filament. The filament was constantly bending after the pulley because of the long distance to the extruder guide, and the force of the motor.   
With this compact design I resolve that problem by reducing the distance as much as possible so the filament is completely guided by the pulley, the idler bearing and the extruder it self. If you have a different pulley and yours does not fit properly with the design, please feel free to comment it and I will make new versions for different pulleys.  
This is the beta 2 so comment any problem or issue you find with the design, please.

description.text:
FIRST: Print the 2 parts in ABS. SECOND: Remove idler supports and drill the holes:
-2 mm for the filament hole.
-3,5 mm for the screw holes.
-3 mm for the hotend screw holes. THIRD: Assemble the extruder, recommended order:
-Insert M3 nuts for the idler screw and the fan (if needed).
-Insert drive Pulley in the motor shaft.
-Attach the Motor to he body with 3 M3x10 screws.
-Assemble the idler separately, use a M3x10 screw for the 623zz bearing. Secure the idler in place with a M3x25 screw.
-Hold the fan in place with two M2x10 screws (if needed).
-Finally use a M3x40 screw with a washer and a spring to make the idler press the filament.

This is a 250 class quadcopter drone that is printed in a single part with no frame assembly required. I designed and built it as part of a course project.

https://youtu.be/1B6fZqDwLBE

This was printed on a Stratasys Dimension BST 1200es in ABS with break-away support at 0.010" layers and solid density.

Parts List

The majority of the parts for the quadcopter were bought from HobbyKing.com. The order quantities, part numbers, and costs are listed below. After shipping, taxes, and other parts purchased, the overall component cost comes out to around $300.

AM1001A $1.97

206000067-0 $15.45

206000068-0 $9.99

9351000063-0 $13.34

TX-9X-M1 $69.64

1x DYS BN5045-R 5x4.5 CW/CCW (Pair) - 2 Pairs/Pack Red
206000101-0 $1.60
